CORDON
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

What it does:
  → marks node as unschedulable
  → NO new pods will be scheduled on this node
  → existing pods keep running normally
  → nothing is moved or deleted

Think of it as:
  "closed for new business
   but existing customers stay"

Command:
  kubectl cordon <node-name>

Undo:
  kubectl uncordon <node-name>

Status after cordon:
  NAME       STATUS                     ROLES
  node1      Ready,SchedulingDisabled   worker


DRAIN
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

What it does:
  → marks node as unschedulable (like cordon)
  → ALSO evicts all existing pods from node
  → pods are rescheduled on other nodes
  → node becomes completely empty

Think of it as:
  "closed for business
   AND existing customers asked to leave"

Command:
  kubectl drain <node-name> \
    --ignore-daemonsets \
    --delete-emptydir-data

Undo:
  kubectl uncordon <node-name>

Flags explained:
  --ignore-daemonsets      → skip daemonset pods
                             (they run on every node anyway)
  --delete-emptydir-data   → delete pods using emptyDir volume
                             (data will be lost)
  --force                  → delete pods not managed by controller


COMPARISON TABLE
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Action                    cordon      drain
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
blocks new pods           ✅ yes      ✅ yes
evicts existing pods      ✗ no        ✅ yes
node becomes empty        ✗ no        ✅ yes
pods rescheduled          ✗ no        ✅ yes
daemonsets removed        ✗ no        ✗ no (skip flag needed)
undo with uncordon        ✅ yes      ✅ yes


WHEN TO USE WHAT
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

cordon → you want to stop new pods going to a node
         but dont want to disturb running pods
         example:
           node showing high CPU
           want to investigate without disruption

drain  → you want to take node completely offline
         for maintenance, upgrade, or replacement
         example:
           patching OS on node
           replacing node hardware
           kubernetes version upgrade
           node is going to be deleted


REAL WORLD FLOW (node maintenance)
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Step 1 → drain the node
         kubectl drain node1 --ignore-daemonsets

Step 2 → do your maintenance
         (patch OS, upgrade kernel, replace hardware)

Step 3 → bring node back
         kubectl uncordon node1

Step 4 → verify node is schedulable again
         kubectl get nodes


WHAT HAPPENS TO DAEMONSETS
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

daemonsets run on EVERY node by design
  example: log collectors, monitoring agents

drain cannot remove daemonset pods
so you must pass --ignore-daemonsets flag
otherwise drain will refuse to run

kubectl drain node1 --ignore-daemonsets ✅


INTERVIEW ONE-LINER
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

"cordon just stops new pods from being scheduled
 on a node. drain goes further — it evicts all
 existing pods too so the node is completely
 empty and safe for maintenance. After maintenance
 we uncordon to bring the node back into
 rotation." ✅
